search:NestJS + Elasticsearch Error Hand.content:
- Use `npm install @nestjs/elasticsearch` to install the NestJS Elasticsearch module.
- Ensure you have the latest version of Node.js and npm installed.
- Import `ElasticsearchModule` in your `app.module.ts`.
- Configure Elasticsearch connection options in `app.module.ts` using `forRoot`.
- Example configuration:
  ```typescript
  import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
  import { ElasticsearchModule } from '@nestjs/elasticsearch';

  @Module({
    imports: [
      ElasticsearchModule.register({
        node: 'http://localhost:9200',
      }),
    ],
  })
  export class AppModule {}
  ```
- Use `@ElasticsearchService` decorator in your service to inject the Elasticsearch client.
- For error handling, create a custom exception filter using NestJS's built-in mechanism.
- Example of a custom exception filter:
  ```typescript
  import { ExceptionFilter, Catch, ArgumentsHost, HttpException } from '@nestjs/common';
  import { Request, Response } from 'express';

  @Catch(HttpException)
  export class ElasticsearchExceptionFilter implements ExceptionFilter {
    catch(exception: HttpException, host: ArgumentsHost) {
      const ctx = host.switchToHttp();
      const response = ctx.getResponse<Response>();
      const request = ctx.getRequest<Request>();

      const status = exception.getStatus();

      response
        .status(status)
        .json({
          statusCode: status,
          timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
          path: request.url,
        });
    }
  }
  ```
- Apply the custom filter in your module or controller:
  ```typescript
  import { Controller, Get } from '@nestjs/common';
  import { ElasticsearchExceptionFilter } from './elasticsearch.exception.filter';

  @Controller('search')
  export class SearchController {
    constructor(private readonly elasticsearchService: ElasticsearchService) {}

    @Get()
    @UseFilters(new ElasticsearchExceptionFilter())
    async search() {
      // Your search logic here
    }
  }
  ```

- Use `nest new project-name` to create a new NestJS project.
- Install `@nestjs/elasticsearch` using `npm install @nestjs/elasticsearch`.
- Configure Elasticsearch in your `app.module.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
  import { ElasticsearchModule } from '@nestjs/elasticsearch';

  @Module({
    imports: [
      ElasticsearchModule.register({
        node: 'http://localhost:9200',
      }),
    ],
  })
  export class AppModule {}
  ```
- Use `@ElasticsearchService` in your services to interact with Elasticsearch.
- Implement custom exception filters for error handling:
  ```typescript
  import { ExceptionFilter, Catch, ArgumentsHost, HttpException } from '@nestjs/common';
  import { Request, Response } from 'express';

  @Catch(HttpException)
  export class HttpExceptionFilter implements ExceptionFilter {
    catch(exception: HttpException, host: ArgumentsHost) {
      const ctx = host.switchToHttp();
      const response = ctx.getResponse<Response>();
      const request = ctx.getRequest<Request>();
      const status = exception.getStatus();

      response
        .status(status)
        .json({
          statusCode: status,
          timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
          path: request.url,
        });
    }
  }
  ```
- Apply the custom filter globally in `main.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import { NestFactory } from '@nestjs/core';
  import { AppModule } from './app.module';
  import { HttpExceptionFilter } from './http-exception.filter';

  async function bootstrap() {
    const app = await NestFactory.create(AppModule);
    app.useGlobalFilters(new HttpExceptionFilter());
    await app.listen(3000);
  }
  bootstrap();
  ```
